    Index 1  16:17:23

@ENDNODE

@NODE WINDOW_AUDIOPLAYER

                     Audio Player
                     ~~~~~~~~~~~~
In this window you can play audio tracks as you are used to from a
CD player. Simply drag the track(s) out of the ReadCDD window and
drop them into the Audio Player window. Of course you you can proceed
in the same way with audio files in the TAO window.


The buttons:

@{b}Play@{ub}
Plays the list beginning with the first track selected.

@{b}Pause@{ub}
Pauses the current track if "Directplay" is activated in the
preferences

@{b}Stop@{ub}
Stops the playback.

@{b}>>@{ub} / @{b}<<@{ub}
Fast forward / rewind

@{b}>>|@{ub} / @{b}|<<@{ub}
Next / previous track

@{b}Del track@{ub}
Deletes selected item from the list.

The fader scans the song in realtime.

@ENDNODE

@NODE WINDOW_AUDIOSTUDIO "Audio studio"

                     Audio Studio
                     ~~~~~~~~~~~~

Now here comes a great new feature of version 2.0. The Audio Studio
gives you the possiblity to edit samples with quite a few high quality
operators.

You can drag & drop items out of the ReadCDD window or load them directly
from the harddrive. After scanning the audio file, it´s amplitude is
displayed.

All available operators are displayed in the Operator window.



Load CDDA file:

        Click on the "?" gadget in the Edit window. A requester will
        pop up asking which CDDA file should be loaded.
        If you wish to load a RAW file, BurnIt will ask you if it
        should be handled as Motorola or Intel format. Which one you
        choose depends on your CD writer, please consult the documention
        of your writer.

        After choosing a CDDA file, BurnIt will load the file. The
        loading speed depends on the set preferences. You can see two
        white amplitudes (left + right channel), which monitor the
        loading process.



        


               Functions in the Editor window
               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

        @{b}Fader@{ub}
                The fader is used to scroll through the display. This
                comes in handy if you zoom in, and not all of the file
                fits into the display.

        @{b}+ / -@{ub}
                Using these buttons you can zoom in / zoom out in
                predefined steps.

        @{b}Mark area@{ub}
                Press the left mouse button in the amplitude window, drag
                it over the entire area you wish to mark, and then let the
                left mouse button go.

        @{b}Zoom range@{ub}
                The marked area is zoomed.

        @{b}Select all@{ub}
                The whole file is selected.

        @{b}Play@{ub}
                The marked area is played using either the Amiga sound
                output or a sound card output. If no file is loaded, this
                function will open a file requester, asking which CDDA
                file to load. During reading the file is also played.
                (full duplex)



       

                Audiobearbeitungsfunktionen (Operatoren)
                ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

        @{b}Paste@{ub}
                A cut or copied area is pasted at the current position.

        @{b}FIRBAND@{ub} (Finity Impluse Response)


        Auf deutsch "Endliche Implus Antwort". Diese Funktion
        ermöglicht Ihnen einen Filter auf einer bestimmten Fre-
        quenzbasis über die Audiodaten zu "legen". 
        Bearbeitet ein bestimmtes Frequenzband, was geboostet
        oder gedämpft wird. Sie können auch verschiedene Fre-
        quenzschranken eingeben.        

        @{b}FIR LOW@{ub}
                High pass filter. Filters out bass frequencies and lets
                high frequencies pass.

        @{b}FIR HIGH@{ub}
                Low pass filter. Filters out the high freqencies, the
                opposite of the FIR LOW.
        
        @{b}Fade OUT@{ub}
                Fades out the music in the marked area. The fade out is
                done according to the settings made.

        @{b}Fade IN-OUT@{ub}
                Fades the in and out of the marked area according to the
                settings made

        @{b}Fade IN@{ub}
                Fades in the music in the marked area. The fade in is
                done according to the settings made.

        @{b}Silence@{ub}
                The marked area is filled with silence (digital 0). This
                comes in handy to keep the background noise down in parts
                which contain no audio signal.        

        @{b}Encode_MP3@{ub}
                Konverts the marked area into an AudioMPEG 3 (layer 3 MPEG)
                file.

        @{b}Dynamic Range@{ub}
                This function optimizes the frequencies and dynamic range
                of a track for output on a CD player. This is needed for
                playbacks from a cassette, because an analog cassette has
                a typical frequence response, depending on the cassette
                type (e.g. Fe). Since this response is nowhere near linear,
                specific frequencies must be boosted and cut. Also keep in
                mind that all analog mediums have a headroom, digital mediums
                don´t have one! So analog recordings normally have more
                dynamics in the peak section. When recording on analog multi-
                track machines, overloading the tape in reasonable sense may be
                wished to use the tape saturation as a so called "tape
                compression". But if you overload a digital medium it sounds
                terrible (digital distortion). Thats why limiting and compress-
                ing the audio signal is a very important chapter of audio CD
                productions. And, of course, you don´t want your CDs to have
                less output volume than other CDs.

        @{b}De-Crackle@{ub}
                This is very powerful operator, which, as the name says, de-
                crackles recordings. Have you ever wanted to backup your old
                vinyl records? Well, here´s the tool.

        @{b}Analyze-FFT 3D@{ub}
                This operator displays the frequency response in a
                3D manner according to the FFT method.

        @{b}Analyze-FFT 2D@{ub}
                This operator displays the frequency response in a
                2D manner according to the FFT method.

        
        @{b}Amplify@{ub}
                Boosts the amplitude of the marked area.

        @{b}Cut@{ub}
                Cuts the marked area.

        @{b}Copy@{ub}
                Copies the marked area.

@ENDNODE

